{{Infobox figure skater |name= Jerry Fotheringill |image= |caption= |fullname= Jerry Joseph Fotheringill |altname= |country= [[United States]] |formercountry= |birth_date= {{birth date and age|1942|3|7}} |birth_place= [[Tacoma, Washington]] |hometown= |residence= |death_date= |death_place= |height= {{convert|180|cm|ft|abbr=on}} |partner= [[Judianne Fotheringill]] |formerpartner= |coach= |formercoach= |choreographer= |formerchoreographer= |skating club= [[Broadmoor SC]] |retired= }} '''Jerry Joseph Fotheringill''' (born March 7, 1942 in [[Tacoma, Washington]]) is an [[United States|American]] former [[pair skater]]. With sister [[Judianne Fotheringill]], he was the [[United States Figure Skating Championships|U.S. national champion]] in 1963 and 1964. They represented the [[United States at the 1964 Winter Olympics]] where [[figure skating at the 1964 Winter Olympics|they placed 7th]].
The Fotheringills were originally from [[Tacoma, Washington]] but later relocated to train in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], where they represented the [[Broadmoor Skating Club]]. Jerry attended [[Colorado College]], where he majored in psychology and political science, during the time he was competing. Jerry was 5'11" tall and three years older than his sister, who was tall for a pair skater at 5'7".<ref>"1963 North American, U.S., & Canadian Champions", ''Skating'' magazine, May 1963</ref>
